"US": {
    "bulario": {
        "nomePrincipioAtivo": "Dipyrone (metamizole sodium)",
        "nomeComercial": "Novalgin®, Magnopyrol®, Anador®, Neo Dormonid®",
        "classificacao": "Analgesic, antipyretic, and antispasmodic; pyrazolone derivative; non-opioid",
        "mecanismoAcao": "Dipyrone exerts analgesic and antipyretic effects by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX), especially COX-3 in the central nervous system, reducing the synthesis of prostaglandins responsible for pain and fever. It also acts on the descending serotonergic pathway and modulates calcium channels in spinal cord neurons. It has an antispasmodic effect through direct action on smooth muscle, distinguishing it from other analgesics. Its active form, 4-methyl-amino-antipyrine, is rapidly formed after oral or parenteral administration and distributed to tissues. Recent studies also suggest dipyrone acts on TRPA1 and TRPV1 channels in the central nervous system, contributing to its potent antinociceptive action, especially in visceral pain and colic. Modulation of the endocannabinoid and serotonin pathways is also involved, explaining part of its efficacy in postoperative and oncological pain. Unlike NSAIDs, it does not strongly inhibit peripheral prostaglandin synthesis, reducing the risk of renal and gastric injury.",
        "farmacocinetica": "• Onset of action: 5–10 min (IV), 30 min (oral), 20 min (IM).\n• Serum peak: 30–90 min.\n• Half-life: 2.5–4 hours (methyl-amino-antipyrine); 6–8 h (other metabolites).\n• Protein binding: ~50–60%.\n• Volume of distribution: 0.5–1.5 L/kg.\n• Metabolism: hepatic (via enzymatic hydrolysis and oxidation).\n• Excretion: renal (conjugated metabolites; reddish urine coloration may occur).\n• Crosses placenta and is present in breast milk in small amounts.",
        "farmacodinamica": "Dipyrone has a potent antipyretic and analgesic effect in mild to moderate acute pain, with efficacy superior to paracetamol in refractory febrile states. It is commonly used in high fever, spasmodic abdominal pain, headache, dental pain, and postoperative pain. Unlike classic NSAIDs, it presents a lower risk of gastric injury and is preferred in patients intolerant to aspirin or ibuprofen. It has a rapid and reliable action via IV in emergency contexts. The antipyretic response occurs by inhibition of prostaglandins in the hypothalamus, while its analgesic effect involves central modulation of pain, with greater efficacy in visceral pain. Dipyrone has a rapid onset and duration of effect of 4–6 h, with greater potency than paracetamol in experimental fever models. When infused slowly, it is well tolerated in septic, oncological, and critical patients, including pediatrics, with consistent response even in refractory fever or complex non-neuropathic pain contexts.",
        "indicacoes": "• Refractory high fever.\n• Mild to moderate acute pain (postoperative, traumatic).\n• Colicky or spasmodic pain (renal, biliary, uterine).\n• Headache and dental pain.\n• Oncological pain as co-analgesic.\n• Safe alternative for patients allergic to NSAIDs and paracetamol.",
        "posologia": "Adults:\n• PO/IM/IV: 500–1000 mg every 6–8 h (maximum 4 g/day).\n• IV should be infused over at least 5 min to avoid hypotension.\nPediatrics:\n• 10–20 mg/kg/dose every 6 h (maximum 60 mg/kg/day or 4 g/day).\n• Neonates: contraindicated (<3 months or <5 kg).",
        "administracao": "• PO: tablets, drops, or oral solution.\n• IV: infuse slowly over 5–10 min (maximum dose 2 g).\n• IM: alternative route, painful, not preferred.\n• Avoid simultaneous administration with incompatible solutions (e.g., bicarbonate).",
        "doseMaxima": "4 g/day (adults); 60 mg/kg/day (pediatrics).",
        "doseMinima": "500 mg PO or IV; 10 mg/kg/dose pediatric.",
        "reacoesAdversas": "Common (1–10%):\n• Nausea, mild hypotension (IV), dizziness.\n• Mild skin reactions (rash).\nUncommon (0.1–1%):\n• Agranulocytosis, leukopenia, anaphylaxis.\n• Severe hypotension (with rapid infusion).\nRare (<0.1%):\n• Stevens-Johnson syndrome, hepatic necrosis, aplastic anemia.\n• Severe allergic reactions in atopic or asthmatic patients.",
        "riscoGravidez": "Category C. Avoid in 1st trimester and near delivery. May be used with caution in 2nd trimester under medical guidance.",
        "riscoLactacao": "Low excretion in milk. Single or short-term use generally safe. Avoid prolonged use without medical supervision.",
        "ajusteRenal": "• CrCl <30 mL/min: extend dosing interval to 8–12 h.\n• CrCl <10 mL/min: maximum 1–2 g/day under monitoring.\n• Dialysis: partially excreted; post-session dose may be considered.",
        "ajusteHepatico": "• Use with caution in severe hepatic impairment.\n• Monitor liver enzymes during prolonged use.",
        "contraindicacoes": "• Hypersensitivity to pyrazolones (e.g., phenylbutazone).\n• Blood dyscrasias, previous agranulocytosis.\n• Concomitant use with high doses of alcohol.\n• Congenital G6PD deficiency (risk of hemolysis).",
        "interacaoMedicamento": "• Increased toxicity with methotrexate, phenytoin, cyclosporine.\n• Potentiation of hypotension with antihypertensives.\n• Increased risk of agranulocytosis with chloramphenicol, sulfonamides.\n• Avoid alcohol during use (disulfiram-like effect in some cases). Dipyrone may potentiate the effect of oral anticoagulants in prolonged treatments, although risk is lower than classic NSAIDs. Concomitant use with immunosuppressants (e.g., azathioprine) or myelotoxic agents (e.g., chemotherapy) requires caution due to combined risk of leukopenia or agranulocytosis. Associations with cyclosporine or methotrexate may increase hematologic and renal toxicity. Simultaneous administration with NSAIDs increases risk of gastrointestinal adverse reactions.",
        "apresentacao": "• Tablets: 500 mg, 1 g.\n• Drops: 500 mg/mL.\n• Oral solution: 50 mg/mL.\n• IV/IM ampoules: 500 mg/mL (1 mL, 2 mL, 5 mL).",
        "preparo": "• IV: dilute in 100 mL of 0.9% saline for infusion over 5–10 min.\n• Drops: dilute in small amount of water.\n• Avoid mixing with alkaline solutions or bicarbonate.",
        "solucoesCompatíveis": "• 0.9% saline, 5% glucose.\n• Incompatible with alkaline solutions and sodium bicarbonate.",
        "armazenamento": "• Store between 15°C and 30°C.\n• Protect from light.\n• Use IV solution within 24 h after opening.",
        "cuidadosMedicos": "• Monitor hematologic function during prolonged use.\n• Investigate history of allergy to pyrazolones.\n• Avoid in patients with increased risk of hematologic dyscrasias.\n• Consider minimum effective dose, especially in elderly and hepatopathic patients.",
        "cuidadosFarmaceuticos": "• Ensure correct dilution and IV compatibility.\n• Educate about risk of hematologic reactions.\n• Clearly document off-label pediatric use.\n• Avoid combination with drugs with additive hematologic risk.",
        "cuidadosEnfermagem": "• Monitor temperature and pain intensity.\n• Observe signs of hypotension, rash, or urticaria.\n• Ensure slow infusion and patent venous access.\n• Immediately report any suspected hematologic changes.",
        "fontesBibliograficas": "Anvisa leaflet (Novalgin®), UpToDate (2024), Micromedex, PubMed ID 37632455, Goodman & Gilman (13th Ed.), Sanford Guide (2023), SBP Pediatric Therapeutic Manual."
